  "prompt": "In India, what are the advantages and disadvantages of living together?",
  "response": "In India, living together (cohabitation) has both advantages and disadvantages:\n\nAdvantages:\n1. Financial benefits\n- Shared living expenses\n- Cost-effective compared to separate households\n- Reduced individual financial burden\n\n2. Relationship understanding\n- Better compatibility assessment\n- Deeper knowledge of each other's habits\n- Mutual compatibility testing before marriage\n\n3. Personal freedom\n- More independence compared to traditional marriages\n- Flexibility in relationship dynamics\n- Less societal pressure\n\n4. Emotional support\n- Companionship\n- Shared responsibilities\n- Mutual care and understanding\n\nDisadvantages:\n1. Social stigma\n- Conservative society often disapproves\n- Family opposition\n- Social judgment and criticism\n\n2. Legal complications\n- Limited legal recognition\n- Lack of property and inheritance rights\n- Uncertain legal status for children\n\n3. Cultural challenges\n- Religious and traditional barriers\n- Potential family conflicts\n- Social exclusion\n\n4. Emotional risks\n- Uncertainty about long-term commitment\n- Potential relationship instability\n- Psychological pressure\n\n5. Professional consequences\n- Potential workplace discrimination\n- Career-related challenges\n- Social reputation impact\n\nDespite increasing acceptance, cohabitation remains complex in India's socio-cultural context.",
